\pagebreak[3]
\addtocounter{subsection}{1}
%\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{\protect
%\numberline{%\arabic{section}
%\arabic{subsection}}
%{#1}}
\noindent{\large\bf %\thesection
\arabic{subsection}.
Closed-String Radiation from a Rolling Probe-Eigenvalue}
\nopagebreak
\vspace{2mm}
\nopagebreak



The surfaces dual to matrix-model diagrams have boundaries if the
matrix model is coupled to variables in the fundamental
representation of the matrix quantum mechanics gauge group
(This fact has been emphasized by
{\it e.g.} \cite{Yang:hs}\cite{Minahan:1992bz}\cite{Kazakov:1991pt}).
Exactly such
variables arise when a classical probe eigenvalue is introduced
into the system, extending the rank of the $N\times N$ matrix
$\TTT$ by one extra row and column \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \TTT_{{}_{N+1 \times \,
N+1}}= \left(\matrix{ z & v_1 & v_2 & \dots \cr v_1^* & T_{11} &
T_{21} & \dots \cr v_2^* & T_{12} & T_{22} &  \dots \cr \dots &
\dots & \dots & \dots
%\cr  \dots       & \dots         & \dots  & \dots & T_{{}_{NN}}
} \right). \end{equation} For fixed extra eigenvalue $z$, the variables $v_i$
have single line propagators that delineate a boundary of the
string world-sheet, with a Dirichlet boundary condition located at
$z$. As a quantitative test of this identification between
eigenvalues of the $c=1$ matrix and D-particles in 2D string
theory, we will compute the closed string radiation produced by a
classical rolling extra eigenvalue in first-order time-dependent
perturbation theory. For the probe trajectory we will take \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\label{rolll} z(t) = \lambda\,  e^t. \end{equation} The corresponding
perturbation hamiltonian arises as follows.


Suppose we start from the  $N\!+\! 1 \times N\!+\! 1$ matrix model. We can
write its wave-function in terms of its eigenvalues and after
splitting off the Vandermonde determinant obtain the free
Hamiltonian $H_{N+1} = H_0 + H_{probe}$. Here $H_0$ is the free
hamiltonian of the $N\times N$ model and $H_{probe}$ that of the
extra eigenvalue. We want to make the probe follow a classical
trajectory. We should therefore consider a wave-function of the
$N$ quantum mechanical eigenvalues only, and rather than factoring
out the complete $N\! +\! 1\times N\! +\! 1$ Vandermonde determinant, we
should split off the $N\times N$ determinant only.
%\be \Psi(\TTT_{{}_{N+1\times\, N+1}}) =
%\prod_{i < j } (\TT_i - \TT_j) ~\psi(z,\TT_1,\ldots,\TT_N). \ee
As a result, the Hamiltonian $H_{N+1}$ does not reduce to the free
Hamiltonian $H_0$ of $N$ non-interacting fermions, but takes the
form \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \label{conjug} H(t) = e^{-W(z(t))} H_0 \, e^{W(z(t))}\, ,
\end{equation} with \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \tilde W(z) = {\rm Tr} \log (z - \TTT ) . \end{equation}
Note that this object may be thought of
as the gauge parameter inducing a background worldvolume gauge field
created by the probe.
Since
the large $N$ theory is semi-classical, we can simplify
(\ref{conjug}) to \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} H = H_0 + H_1\, , \qquad \qquad H_1 = [ H_0,
\tilde W\lb z(t)\rb]. \end{equation}



We want to compute the transition amplitude from an initial state
$\ket{\mu_{{}_{\! F}}}$, in which the Fermi sea of the $N$ eigenvalues is
calm and quiet, to a final state $\ket{\mu_{{}_{\! F}} + \omega}$ with a
single excitation with energy $\omega$.
In first-order time-dependent perturbation theory,
this amplitude takes the form \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\label{ohm}
\CA(\omega) = \int \!\! dt\, \bra{\mu_{{}_{\! F}}+ \omega }\,
 [ H_0, \tilde W\lb z(t)\rb]\,
\ket{\mu_{{}_{\! F}}}  = \omega \int \!\! dt\, \bra{\mu_{{}_{\! F}} + \omega } \, \tilde
W\lb z(t)\rb \ket{\mu_{{}_{\! F}}} \end{equation} The matrix operator $W(z)$ is related
via a Laplace transform to the ``macroscopic loop operator''
$W(\ell)$ that creates a boundary to the string world sheet with
total boundary length $\ell$: \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \tilde W(z) =
\int\limits_0^\infty \!{d\ell \over \ell}\, e^{- z \ell}
~W(\ell)\, \qquad \qquad W(\ell) \equiv {\rm Tr} \, e^{\ell \,
\TTT }. \end{equation} The relevant amplitude of the macroscopic loop
operators $W(\ell)$ have been evaluated in \cite{Moore:1991ir}
\cite{Kazakov:1991pt}, with the result \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \label{loop}
\vev{\mu_{{}_{\! F}}+\omega| W(\ell) |\mu_{{}_{\! F}} } = e^{-i\delta(\omega)}
K_{i\omega} (\sqrt \mu \, \ell ) \end{equation} with $\mu = \mu_c-\mu_{{}_{\! F}}$ as
before, and where we have included the phase
$e^{-i\delta(\omega)}$ as defined in equation (\ref{leg}). This phase
is not produced by the matrix model itself, but appears as a
separate wave-function renormalization, the so-called leg-pole
factor, that relates the matrix model states to the continuum
closed string tachyon modes (see for example Eqn. (7.27) of
\cite{Klebanov:1991qa}).

Combining (\ref{ohm}) with (\ref{loop}) and the
integral formula (\ref{geez}) gives \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
 \CA(\omega) =
\int \!\! dt\, e^{-i\delta(\omega)} { \cos \lb\pi \omega \, s(t)\rb \over \sinh (\pi \omega)}
\end{equation} where $s(t)$ parametrizes the probe trajectory via
\begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} z(t) = \cosh\lb \pi s(t)\rb \end{equation} Now for the rolling
trajectory (\ref{rolll}) we have
 \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \label{probeelement}
\int \!\! dt\, \cos (\pi \omega s(t))
 = \int \!\!
d s \, \rho(s) \, \cos (\pi \omega s). \end{equation} with \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \rho(s) =
{dt\over ds} =  {\pi \over 1 + e^{2\pi s}} - {\pi \over 1 +
e^{-2\pi s}}. \end{equation} We can view this quantity $\rho$ as the
semi-classical expression of the quantum mechanical probability
density $|\psi(s)|^2$ of the probe eigenvalue. It is interesting
to note that this expression has poles exactly at the allowed
values of the Liouville boundary state parameter $s$ discussed
earlier \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace} \qquad \ \ \ s ={i\over 2} (2m+1) \qquad  \ \ m \in
{\bf Z}. \end{equation} These values of $s$ correspond to the location $z=0$
at the top of the inverted harmonic potential. The physical origin
of the poles in $\rho(s)$ is of course that the critical
trajectory (\ref{rolll}) has zero velocity at this location, while
the periodic recurrence of the poles reflects the periodic orbits
of the right-side up harmonic oscillator.

