To perform the integral
(\ref{probeelement}), we can write $\cos(\pi\omega s) ={1\over 2}( e^{i\pi \omega s}+e^{-i\pi \omega s})$ and in
each of the two terms we can close the contour in the upper and lower
half complex $s$-plane respectively, giving \begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\int \!\! ds \,\rho(s) \, \cos (\pi \omega s )\,
%\pi \left( \sum_{n\geq 0} e^{
%i \omega (\tilde \tau_n - t)} + \sum_{n<0} e^{ -i \omega (\tilde
%\tau_n - t)} \right)
= {\pi \over \sinh (\pi \omega/2)}
%\cos
%\left(\omega (\ln 2 \pi \lambda + t) \right)
\end{equation}
The final answer for the production amplitude
\begin{equation}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayskip}{\extraspaces}
\addtolength{\abovedisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\addtolength{\belowdisplayshortskip}{\extraspace}
\label{repro}
\CA(\omega) = {\pi \, e^{-i
\delta(\omega)}
\over \sinh (\pi \omega/2) \sinh(\pi \omega)}
\end{equation}
precisely reproduces (up to an unobservable phase factor $\lambda^{-i\omega}$,
which represents a constant time-delay) the
continuum result (\ref{production}). This confirms our interpretation of the extra
eigenvalue as an unstable D-particle of the 1+1-d string theory.
%\be
%A(\omega) = \mu^{- i \omega/2} { \Gamma( 1 + i \omega) \over \Gamma( 1 - i \omega) }
%{ \pi \over  \sinh \pi \omega} ( 2 \pi \lambda)^{- i \omega}
%\ee

It is in principle straightforward to compute the higher order corrections to the
leading order result (\ref{repro}). To find a sensible total production rate, however,
one would need to treat the probe quantum mechanically, so that the recoil is included
and total energy is preserved. It is evident from the matrix description that
all the initial energy (of order $1/\mu$) of the D-particle will be emitted in
the form of closed string tachyon radiation.







